Summary of every bug found, why it happened, and exactly what I changed
1) "Add Aspirant" button did nothing
- Bug: The original file relied on inline onclick attributes and/or DOM elements referenced with IDs that were inconsistent. In some cases the button ID differed from the code that tried to attach handlers; when scripts executed before DOM readiness, event binding could fail. Also there was inconsistent wiring between inline handlers and dynamically-scoped functions (if functions were moved inside a DOMContentLoaded wrapper they became non-global and inline onclick could not call them).
- Why: Event listeners were not reliably attached; initialization timing/IDs mismatch caused the click to not call the addRow logic.
- Fix: Added a robust initialization block that runs on DOMContentLoaded (or immediately if ready) and attaches event listeners to the Add button (id="add-btn"). Kept the inline compatibility by exposing addRow on window. Added console.log on click. Ensured addRow is a top-level function (global) and always works. Also replaced the inline "Import CSV" control wiring with explicit listeners.

2) CSV Import produced truncated name/email values (e.g., "Sh" and "o")
- Bug: The original CSV parsing and row creation used fragile innerHTML injection for building the row with oninput attributes; when values contained quotes, commas, or special characters, attribute injection caused broken attribute values. In some cases the input values read from DOM were truncated because the innerHTML or attribute string ended early.
- Why: Using template HTML with unescaped values and oninput handlers in the string caused attribute parsing issues; the simplistic CSV parser in the original file also didn't handle quoted fields and escaped quotes properly.
- Fix:
  - Replaced the row DOM building with element-by-element createElement and addEventListener calls (no HTML string injection). This prevents attribute parsing/escaping bugs that caused truncation.
  - Rewrote parseCSVLine to correctly handle quoted fields, escaped double-quotes inside quoted fields, and commas inside quoted fields. Normalized CRLF to LF before splitting lines.
  - Import now trims and maps columns robustly; skip header if first line looks like header.
  - Added console logs/warnings for skipped rows.

3) Brevo error "email is not valid in to"
- Bug: The sent payload sometimes included truncated email addresses (first character) because of the DOM injection problem above; also there was no client-side email format validation, so invalid emails were sent to Brevo.
- Why: Truncated email values lead Brevo to reject the recipient; lack of validation allowed invalid addresses to be attempted.
- Fix:
  - Ensure the full email value is read from the rows array (which is correctly updated from inputs).
  - Add isValidEmail() check before attempting to send; skip rows with invalid emails and log error.
  - Add detailed console.error logs when Brevo responds with errors (including body), to help debugging.

4) Undefined variables, duplicate IDs, broken selectors, DOM timing
- Bugs:
  - Some code used element IDs or selectors that didn't exist or changed.
  - Handlers could be added before DOM ready.
  - Duplicate IDs could occur if code used static IDs per row; ensured unique IDs using generated id per row.
- Why: The code was mixing inline event attributes, string-based innerHTML, and dynamic creation leading to inconsistencies and timing issues.
- Fix:
  - Created stable unique numeric id per row (Date.now + random).
  - Ensured all DOM queries check for existence and log errors when missing.
  - Attached listeners after DOM ready; still exposed functions to window for compatibility.
  - Ensured no duplicate ID usage.

5) Preservation of all features / UI unchanged
- Action: Kept all original UI structure and features:
  - CSV import (now robust)
  - Add Aspirant
  - Delete row
  - Edit row (inputs update rows array)
  - Send emails via Brevo API
  - Status updates (row dot changes)
  - Progress bar
  - Export CSV template
  - Template preview
- Note: Implementation is behind-the-scenes cleaner but the UI and available features are intact.

6) Console logging for debugging
- Action: Added console.log for key actions (initialization, add/remove rows, CSV import start/finish, send start/complete, per-row send attempts) and console.error for failures (file read errors, invalid rows, Brevo failures). This will help debugging in the browser console without changing UI.

7) Other defensive improvements
- FileReader error handling
- Revoke object URLs after download
- Resetting file input after import so same file can be re-imported
- Progress bar updates and log display behavior improved
- Exposed functions on window to keep compatibility with existing inline handlers (if any)

Notes on testing
